ops.insert: International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market?

textDelta: International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market? The answer is that trade is not costless. Trade costs include the costs of acquiring new technology, the costs of adapting to new competition, and the costs of moving production facilities to other countries. The costs of trade are often greater than the benefits, so countries may try to protect their firms from trade.
